<item>
            <title>[GROOVY-10800] The % operator returns unexpected results for negative numbers for BigIntegers</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/GROOVY-10800</link>
                <project id="12318123" key="GROOVY">Groovy</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;As a follow-up to&#160;&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/GROOVY-10786&quot; title=&quot;Cannot call modulo operator (%) on BigDecimal types&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;GROOVY-10786&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;GROOVY-10786&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, the behavior of the % operator for BigInteger is a little strange for negative numbers.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;code panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;codeContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre class=&quot;code-java&quot;&gt;
def nums = [-10, -10L, -10f, -10d, -10G, -10.0G]
&lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;assert&lt;/span&gt; nums.collect{ it % 3 } == [-1, -1, -1f, -1d, 2G, -1.0G]
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In our documentation, we call &quot;%&quot; the remainder operator as does Java, though also like Java, the operator is often informally referred to as the &quot;mod&quot; operator. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I suggest we change the BigInteger &quot;%&quot; operator to be the same as the other numeric types, i.e. use remainder not mod.&lt;br/&gt;
This has some ramifications which I&apos;ll bring up on the mailing list.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
